<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION SELECT COMMITTEE (PASC)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Further Written Evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the Information Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> [OD26]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">This is the response of the Information Commissioner to the </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">call by the Public Administration Select Committees (PASC) for further evidence on statistics and open data. It covers the following points:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Introduction</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">General comments on the UK National Action</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> Plan</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Comments on commitment 3 - transparency in local government </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Comments on the issue of transparency in contracting (commitments 4, 9 and 12)</span></li></ul><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Information Commissioner (“the Commissioner”) has responsibility for promoting and enforcing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA) and the Freedom of Information Act 2000 (FOIA), together with associated legislation such as the Environmental Information Regulations (EIR) and the Privacy and Electronic Communications (EC Directive) Regulations 2003 (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">PECR).</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">He is independent from government and upholds information rights in the public interest, promoting openness by public bodies and data privacy for individuals and taking appropriate action where the law is broken.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner made a full </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">submission</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> to the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Public Administration Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> in September 2013</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">He now</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> makes the following submission in response to the Committee’s call for further evidence.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">In particular, he wishes to comment on the </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/255901/ogp_uknationalactionplan.pdf"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">UK National Action Plan</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> for open government 2013-2015</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> (NAP)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, launched at the Open Government Partnership Summit in October 2013. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK National Action Plan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> general comments</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner welcomes the evidence in the National Action Plan of the UK’s achievements to date in the field of open data, and the government’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">commitment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> to open government.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">  In particular he welcomes the broader range of commit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ments, compared to the previous plan.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">He considers that open data and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the right to information, as enacted in the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), are mutually supportive.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Effective o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">pen government requires both open data policies and a statutory right </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to information</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">; in other words, there must be a right for the public to ‘pull’ information from government as well as a government commitment to ‘push’ data out proactively. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">FOIA is often needed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> to ask the difficult questions, not covered by information o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">r data proactively disclosed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">FOIA acts as a statutory safeguard to ensure that information which is accessible from public authorities is not limited to that which they have decided to publish proactively. At the same time, t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">he government’s open data poli</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">cies have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">also assisted publ</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ic</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> authorities </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">responding to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">FOIA</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> requests</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, by setting </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">benchmarks for the information which should generally be released</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency in local government (commitment 3)</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">considers that the Local Authorities Data Transparency Code has made a significant contribution to openness and transparency in local government, and he </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">strongly </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">supports </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the move to widen the scope of what is routinely made available. As noted above, he a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">lso considers that this assists local authorities in handling FOIA requests. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 16.99pt; padding-left:11.36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Nevertheless</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, he has concerns about the government’s intention “to bring into force regulations making it a legal requirement for local authorities to publish data in accordance </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">with the Code”</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">(NAP page 14)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Firstly, the approach of making it a legal requirement to publish </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">datasets according to a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">pecific and detailed list</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, drawn up by government at a point in time</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> appears antithetical to the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">spirit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">of open data. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">What datas</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ets are most useful and most aid transparency will vary or increase over time. Open data -</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">and more broadly, open government – does not sit well with an approach that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> knows best what data is required and sanctions those who do not comply. Rather</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, the open data agenda depends on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">a dialogue between </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> and those who want to use and re-use </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> data. It should be recognised that the people who will want to obta</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">n and use these large </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">datasets</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">likely to be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">principally information </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">intermediaries (data jour</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">na</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">lists, researchers, app developers etc</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">) rather than the individual citizens; the latter are more likely to gain their insight into the workings of local government through the products </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">and publications </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">developed by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">those interme</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">diaries or</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> alternatively </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">through making FOIA requests.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> The Commissioner is in favour of a balance between legal requirements, which are important, and guidance about those requirements which can be responsive and flexible over time.  Much of this can alrea</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">dy be achieved under FOIA.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Secondly, the Commissioner has concerns about the enforcement of this legal requirement. He notes the government’s commitment to:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">work with the Local Government Association (LGA) and the Information Commissioner’s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Office to adop</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t a light touch approach to monitoring and enforcement and determine levels</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of compliance during the 2014 to 2015 period</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> (NAP page 14)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">”</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Public</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> authorities </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">have a duty under FOIA to adopt and maintain a publication scheme and to publish </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">information</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">in accordance with that scheme. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Public</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> authorities use a model scheme created and approved by the Commissioner for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">purpose</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, and the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> ha</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> issued ‘</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">definition</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> documents’ listing the information that he expects </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">public </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">authorities to make avail</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">able under their </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">publication scheme. The Commissioner has worked to ensure that the definition document for local government reflects the current Local Authorities Data Transparency Code. </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">in favour of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">more collaborative approach to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">improving the transparency of local go</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">vernment. The current proposal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> will </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">create</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> substantial areas of duplication, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">with no clear justification</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">.  A further statutory scheme will create confusion for the public and local authorities.  The additional costs th</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">at may be created by a further statutory scheme are also difficult to justify.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> The Commissioner has questioned the feasibility of what is proposed. It is also important that the Commissioner maintains his independence</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> as the body responsible for promoting </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">and enforcing FOIA</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency in contracting (commitments 4, 9 and 12) </span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">notes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the government’s endorsement of the principles of open contracting in Commitment 12, the aim of greater transparency on public service contracts in Commitmen</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">t 4 and the promotion of the principles of transparency and accountability in government-funded construction projects in Commitment 9.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">welcomes this commitment to transparency about the process of procuring services, works and goods. He </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">wo</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">uld </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">also make the point that the availability of information about the delivery </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">of contracts and the performance of the contractor </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">is equally important. The Commissioner’s experience is that this information is often requested under FOIA. Opening this info</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">rmation as fully as possible to public scrutiny would promote efficiency in the use of public funds and also help to build public confidence in outsourcing. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">therefore welcomes</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> the commitment on page 31 of the NAP to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“take steps to ensure</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> transparency about outsourced services is provided in response to freedom of information requests, by encouraging the use and enforcement of contractual provisions to maintain the levels of transparency provided by the Freedom of Information Act 2000; rev</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ised guidance will be provided in 2014”.</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">As the Commissioner has previously </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">outlined</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">it is important that outsourcing does not lead to a decrease in transparency in public services.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner also awaits the full details of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">government’s imple</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">mentation of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> response </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the Justice Select Committee’s report on post legislative scrutiny of FOIA</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. Section 8 of the report covered   </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">application of FO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">I to outsourced public services.  This may potentially include a revision of the section 45 Code of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> Practice issued under FOIA.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner would point out that information is only accessible under FOIA if it is held by or on behalf of a public authority. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">This leads to a key question: when a contractor who is paid out of public funds is delivering a service on behalf of a </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">public</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> authority, is the information that the contractor holds about the delivery of that service held on behalf of the public authority?</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> If so, it is potentially accessible under FOIA; if not, then it is not accessible. A contractual provision that merely requires a contractor to co-operate in a general way with the public authority when the latter receives a FOIA request does not adequate</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">ly address this problem. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">It is the Commissioner’s view that a simple FOIA/transparency clause may not always have the desired effect if other potentially contradictory elements of the contract are not addressed.  An “open by default” approach must be taken</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> to the contract as a whole.</span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The CBI recently published a set of transparency principles for providers </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">public services</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> The Commissioner welcomes this </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">initiative </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">and he </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">is seeking to encourage much better dialogue between commissioners and providers t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">o </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">develop </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">a much better general understanding of what “open by default”, in relation outsourced public services, looks like.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 12pt 24.62pt; padding-left:3.73pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">The Commissioner will consider whether he needs to provide guidance on these relevant issues</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> related to FOIA and the EIR in 2014</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">. This could include fuller guidance on </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">legal approach to be taken to requests and whether information is held and new guidance containing examples of best practice in contractual provisions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><br /><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Evidence of the Information Commissioner to PASC Inquiry into statistics and open data.  Published 8 October 2013. </span><a href="http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/WrittenEvidence.svc/EvidenceHtml/1748"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://data.p</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">arliament.uk/writtenevidence/WrittenEvidence.svc/EvidenceHtml/1748</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Justice Select Committee (2012) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Post-legislative scrutiny of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Freedom of Information Act 200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">HC 96-I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmjust/96/9611.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; te